===============================================================================
LINKING EXCEPTION (applies only to option (B) above)
===============================================================================

As a special exception, the copyright holders of LiveContainer give you
additional permission to:

  1. Link or combine LiveContainer with independent modules to produce
     an executable, regardless of the license terms of those independent
     modules, and to copy and distribute the resulting executable under
     terms of your choice, provided that you also meet, for each linked
     independent module, the terms and conditions of the license of
     that module. An independent module is a module which is not
     derived from or based on LiveContainer.

  2. Distribute the resulting Combined Work through any application
     distribution platform (including, without limitation, the Apple
     App Store, Google Play, or similar curated distribution channels),
     notwithstanding any technical or contractual restrictions imposed
     by such channels that would otherwise prevent compliance with
     Section 4(d) and Section 4(e) of the GNU Lesser General Public
     License version 3, or that would impose terms inconsistent with
     Section 10 of the GNU General Public License version 3.

  3. Combine LiveContainer with code statically linked into a single
     binary, even when the runtime environment of that binary (such as
     a sandboxed iOS or iPadOS application) does not permit end users
     to replace the linked copy of LiveContainer with a modified
     version, provided that the source code of LiveContainer and any
     modifications to it remain available under this License.

If you modify LiveContainer itself, the source code of those
modifications must still be made available under the GNU Lesser
General Public License version 3 (or later), as required by Section 5
of the LGPL. This exception covers only the linking and distribution
of the Combined Work; it does not weaken the copyleft on LiveContainer
itself.

If you modify LiveContainer, you may extend this exception to your
version of the library, but you are not obligated to do so. If you do
not wish to do so, delete this exception statement from your version.

This exception is modeled on the "Classpath exception" used by GNU
Classpath and OpenJDK, and on the GCC Runtime Library Exception. Its
purpose is to make LiveContainer usable as a library inside
proprietary applications distributed through closed application stores
(notably the Apple App Store), while preserving the copyleft on
LiveContainer's own source code.


===============================================================================
DUAL-LICENSED COMPONENTS
===============================================================================

The following paths are available under option (A) OR option (B), at
the recipient's choice:

  LiveContainer/LCBootstrap.*
  LiveContainer/LCMachOUtils.*
  LiveContainer/LCSharedUtils.*
  LiveContainer/Localization.*
  LiveContainer/utils.*
  LiveContainer/dyld_bypass_validation.*
  LiveContainer/FoundationPrivate.h
  LiveContainer/UIKitPrivate.h
  LiveContainer/Tweaks/**

  LiveContainerSwiftUI/Models/LCAppInfo.*
  LiveContainerSwiftUI/Utilities/LCUtils.*
  LiveContainerSwiftUI/Utilities/IconServices.*
  LiveContainerSwiftUI/Utilities/unarchive.*

  ZSign/**                  (see "ZSIGN PROVENANCE" note below)

The "**" suffix means "all files in this directory and subdirectories".
The ".*" suffix means "all files with this base name regardless of
extension" (for example, LCBootstrap.* covers LCBootstrap.h,
LCBootstrap.m, LCBootstrap.mm, etc.).

All other paths in this repository (including but not limited to
LiveContainerSwiftUI/App/, LiveContainerSwiftUI/Views/,
LaunchAppExtension/, LaunchAppExtensionHelper/, LiveProcess/,
MultitaskSupport/, Resources/, SideStore/, TestJITLess/, and the
LiveContainer Xcode project files) are available under option (A)
ONLY.

If you have a question about whether a specific file is dual-licensed,
open an issue. The list above is authoritative.


===============================================================================
HOW TO CHOOSE
===============================================================================

If you are forking LiveContainer for use in another open source project,
or running a service based on LiveContainer, option (A) (AGPL-3.0) is
typically the right choice and applies to the full repository.

If you wish to embed LiveContainer's runtime, signing, or related
support components as a library inside a closed-source application
(for example, an iOS application distributed through the Apple App
Store), option (B) (LGPL-3.0 with the Linking Exception) is intended
for you, and is available for the components enumerated in
"DUAL-LICENSED COMPONENTS" above.

You are required to comply with all terms of the license you select,
including any attribution, source-availability, and modification-
disclosure requirements.


===============================================================================
ZSIGN PROVENANCE
===============================================================================

ZSign in this repository originates from https://github.com/zhlynn/zsign
(licensed under the MIT License) and was further modified in
https://github.com/khcrysalis/Feather (licensed under GPL-3.0) before
being vendored and additionally modified in LiveContainer.

The dual-license offer for ZSign above is made on the following basis:

  - The original zsign code by zhlynn is under the MIT License, which
    permits sublicensing under any terms, including the dual-license
    offered here.

  - Modifications made within LiveContainer by contributors who have
    consented to dual-licensing (see RELICENSING.md) are dual-licensed
    under the terms above.

  - Modifications inherited from khcrysalis/Feather (GPL-3.0) require
    explicit consent from the relevant copyright holders before they
    can be distributed under option (B). Until that consent is recorded
    in RELICENSING.md, recipients relying on option (B) for ZSign must
    either (i) verify that the specific ZSign code they use does not
    contain copyrightable portions inherited from khcrysalis/Feather,
    or (ii) obtain a separate license grant from the relevant
    copyright holders.

A recipient who in good faith uses ZSign under option (B) before this
consent process is complete should not be treated as a license
violator if they cease use or obtain the necessary consent within a
reasonable cure period after notice. This paragraph does not waive any
third party's rights.


